<h1>@Vte{{}}@HI{{aru}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li>@EM{{@Vte{{}}@HI{{aru}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@Vte{{}}@HI{{aru}}}} is used as an auxiliary verb with the @HI{{te}}-form.
This sentence pattern expresses the idea that someone performed an action and the state
resulting from that action persists until the present time. The agent that performed
the action is most often omitted, because the agent is unknown, unimportant or obvious.
</p>


<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> @KJ{{window}}@HI{{ga ai@EM{{te aru}}.}}</td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td> The window has been opened <em>(for some purpose</em>). </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KT{{karenda-}}@HI{{ni}}@KJ{{now}}@KJ{{month}}@HI{{no}}@KJ{{beforehand}}@KJ{{determine}}@HI{{ga}}
      @KJ{{write}}@HI{{i@EM{{tearimasu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This month's schedule is written on the calendar.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KT{{hoteru}}@HI{{ha mou}} @KJ{{beforehand}}@KJ{{promise}}@HI{{shi<strong>te arimasu<strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I have already reserved a hotel.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The sentence
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> @KJ{{window}}@HI{{ga}}@KJ{{open}}@HI{{ketearu.}}</td> </tr>
</table>
implies not only that the window is open but that someone opened it.
</p>

<p>
The sentence
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> @KJ{{window}}@HI{{ga}}@KJ{{open}}@HI{{teiru.}}</td> </tr>
</table>
implies only that the window is open, making no inference about how it reached that state.
</p>

<p>
Finally, The sentence
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> @KJ{{private}}@HI{{ha}}@KJ{{window}}@HI{{wo}}@KJ{{open}}@HI{{keteoku.}}</td> </tr>
</table>
indicates that I opened the window for a future purpose.
</p>

